<statement>
<p>A triangle has sides with lengths <m>\displaystyle{a}={4.00}</m>, <m>\displaystyle{b}={5.04}</m>, and <m>\displaystyle{c}={4.28}</m>. Calculate all of the angles of this triangle.</p>
<p>A=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{a}={4.00}</m>)</p>
<p>
  B=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{b}={5.04}</m>)</p>
<p>
  C=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{c}={4.28}</m>)</p>
<p>Round to two decimal places.</p>


</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li>50.02</li><li>74.9</li><li>47.61</li></ul></p><p>Because we have all three sides, we can use the law of cosines for the first angle.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{4}^{{2}}={5.04}^{{2}}+{4.28}^{{2}}-{2}{\left({5.04}\right)}{\left({4.28}\right)}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{16}={25.4016}+{18.3184}-{43.1424}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{27.72}=-{43.1424}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{0.64252336448598}={\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{A}={50.019761183174}={50.02}</m>.</p>
<p>For a second angle, we can use the shorter law of sines.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{\sin{{\left({50.019761183174}\right)}}}}{{4.00}}=\frac{{\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}}{{5.04}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{0.30650255586456}={\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={\arcsin{{\left(-{0.30650255586456}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={74.904981812528}\approx{74.9}</m></p>
<p>The third angle we can calculate using the angle sum property.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{50.019761183174}+{74.904981812528}+{C}={180}^{\circ}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{C}={47.611133693139}\approx{47.61}</m></p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

